{"id": "duc04-testb-49:9#28", "contents": "IMF officials claim that they are adapting their strategies to minimize the social costs of their actions. They argue that finding the right balance between discipline and flexibility is a difficult formula, but one that is necessary to prevent suffering while also maintaining economic stability. In recent months, the IMF has allowed more spending to sustain subsidies for basic goods in countries such as Indonesia and Korea. This new flexibility has been welcomed by some, including a senior Indonesian official who noted that the IMF is now more responsive to the needs of its member countries."}
